Woobie Module

This is a demonstrative module intended as a template and starting point
for developing custom Eggdrop modules.

REQUIREMENTS

None.

LOADING

Put this line into your Eggdrop configuration file to load the woobie
module:

    loadmodule woobie

CONFIGURATION

No configuration options are available.

DESCRIPTION

The woobie module serves as a minimal, well-documented example of module
structure and API usage. It is not intended for production use but rather
as educational material for developers.

SOURCE CODE LOCATION

The woobie module source is located at:

    src/mod/woobie.mod/woobie.c

STUDY GUIDE

If you are writing a custom module, examine woobie.c to learn:

1. Module structure: required entry points (MODULE_start, MODULE_close,
   MODULE_expmem, MODULE_report)

2. Function exports: how to create and manage MODULE_table

3. Hook registration: adding and removing hooks for periodic functions

4. Memory management: using nmalloc and nfree safely

5. Error handling: returning appropriate error strings

6. Logging: using putlog for debugging

For comprehensive module development documentation, see
doc/modules/writing-modules.

GETTING STARTED

To create your own module based on woobie:

1. Copy src/mod/woobie.mod to src/mod/mymodule.mod
2. Rename woobie.c to mymodule.c
3. Replace all instances of 'woobie' with 'mymodule' in:
   - mymodule.c (MODULE_NAME define)
   - meson.build
4. Modify the module's functionality as desired
5. Build with: meson setup builddir/ && ninja -C builddir/

MODULE API REFERENCE

The module has access to the Eggdrop function table through the global
'Function *global' pointer. See src/mod/module.h for available functions:

Memory
  nmalloc, nfree

Hooks
  add_hook, del_hook

Modules
  module_register, module_undepend, module_find, module_load, module_unload

Tcl Integration
  add_tcl_commands, rem_tcl_commands
  add_tcl_ints, rem_tcl_ints
  add_tcl_strings, rem_tcl_strings
  add_builtins, rem_builtins

I/O
  dprintf, putlog

Each function is well-documented in module.h with parameter descriptions.

BEST PRACTICES

When creating modules, follow these guidelines (demonstrated by woobie):

1. Use static for internal functions to reduce symbol bloat

2. Keep MODULE_start simple; defer complex initialization to hooks

3. Always return NULL on success; non-NULL error strings on failure

4. Clean up all allocated resources in MODULE_close

5. Use proper error handling — never assume operations succeed

6. Document your module's configuration options clearly

7. Test memory with the .status partyline command

For more detailed guidelines, see doc/modules/writing-modules.

EXAMPLE OUTPUT

When loaded, woobie produces minimal output. Check bot logs for:
  "[module] Woobie module loaded"

DOCUMENTATION TEMPLATE

Use woobie as a template for writing module documentation:

1. Brief one-line description
2. Requirements section
3. Loading instructions
4. Configuration options
5. Description section with usage examples
6. Troubleshooting if applicable

